{"attrs": {"n_facts": 9, "text": "Under unconfoundedness, weighted split conformal prediction with weights given by the likelihood ratio between the test covariate distribution and the calibration distribution (the inverse propensity score) yields a prediction interval for the counterfactual outcome with valid marginal coverage at level 1 minus alpha; combined with a nested procedure this produces intervals for the individual treatment effect."}, "id": "result::arxiv-2006.06138-main", "kind": "result", "label": "arxiv-2006.06138-main", "provenance": "arxiv-2006.06138-main"}
{"attrs": {"n_facts": 1, "text": "Importance weighting: the likelihood ratio between a target distribution and a source distribution is the density ratio whose expectation reweights source samples to the target."}, "id": "result::importance_weighting", "kind": "result", "label": "importance_weighting", "provenance": "importance_weighting"}
{"attrs": {"n_facts": 4, "text": "Split conformal prediction: given exchangeable calibration and test data, the prediction interval built from the empirical quantile of the calibration nonconformity scores attains valid marginal coverage at level 1 minus alpha."}, "id": "result::split_conformal", "kind": "result", "label": "split_conformal", "provenance": "split_conformal"}
{"attrs": {"n_facts": 7, "text": "Weighted conformal prediction under covariate shift: when the test covariate distribution differs from the calibration distribution, reweighting the calibration scores by the likelihood ratio between the two distributions restores weighted exchangeability of the calibration and test data, so the resulting prediction interval attains valid marginal coverage at level 1 minus alpha."}, "id": "result::weighted_conformal", "kind": "result", "label": "weighted_conformal", "provenance": "weighted_conformal"}
